  <h2>The mental model</h2>
  <p>
    Tax planning is mostly about three levers: <strong>which allowances I use</strong>,
    <strong>when income/gains land</strong>, and <strong>which wrapper holds an asset</strong>.
    Small, repeatable habits beat clever one-offs.
  </p>

  <h2>Allowances to check every year</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Personal allowance — the tax-free slice of income; watch for tapering at higher incomes.</li>
    <li>ISA allowance — use it or lose it; can't carry forward.</li>
    <li>Pension annual allowance — plus any unused allowance carried forward from prior years.</li>
    <li>Capital gains exempt amount — realise gains up to it; consider spreading disposals across tax years.</li>
    <li>Dividend and savings allowances — affect how investment income is taxed.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Timing levers</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Defer or accelerate a disposal to land a gain in the more favourable tax year.</li>
    <li>Bring forward deductible costs / pension contributions to manage the marginal rate.</li>
    <li>Spread a large gain across two tax years to use two annual exemptions.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Wrapper order of preference (rough)</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Pension — tax relief on the way in, but locked until pension age.</li>
    <li>ISA — no tax on growth/withdrawals, fully flexible.</li>
    <li>General account — taxable, but no contribution cap; use allowances to soften it.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Questions to bring to an adviser</h2>
  <blockquote>
    What's my marginal rate this year vs next? · Am I leaving any allowance unused? ·
    Does my income sit near a threshold where a small change has an outsized effect?
  </blockquote>

